<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
The species is named after the collector, Ludwig H.P. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="DÃ¶derlein">Doederlein</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<pageBreakToken pageId="15" pageNumber="16" start="start">Remarks</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The coenenchymal clubs of this species look like flower buds, similar to those described for 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Melitaea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Melitaea retifera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="retifera">Melitaea retifera</taxonomicName>
Lamarck, 1916 by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ofwegen, LP van" journalOrPublisher="Zoologische Mededelingen Leiden" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="285 - 304" title="The Melithaeidae (Coelenterata: Octocorallia) of Singapore." volume="73" year="2000">Ofwegen et al. (2000)</bibRefCitation>
, but that species has unilaterally foliate spheroids, a type of sclerite not present in the present material.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
